{"parentUuid":"c4c3d36a-1f3d-4e01-b135-110c52140bdf","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1e20eae898f4be33","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcqhivVrPBSH9v6Ct7ehF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Summary\n\n**Suite run:** 127 passed, 0 failed, 0 skipped (full `pytest tests/ -k \"not dashboard\"` — the `dashboard` files are stray leftovers from a different branch's working tree, correctly excluded; this feature is `metric-quotas`, not the dashboard).\n\n**Coverage (combined):** lines 90.3%, branches **58.3%** (call-out: branch coverage is notably weaker than line coverage — mostly in `src/observability/sentry.py`, `src/repositories/*`, `src/services/events_service.py` error-path branches not exercised), functions not tracked (coverage.py has no function metric).\n\n**Shape:** `pyramid` per plan.md, realized unit 80 / integration 47 / e2e 0 — consistent with the declared strategy.\n\n**New test I added (adversarial, not written by implementation):** `tests/integration/test_quotas_rls_backstop.py` — the repo/migration explicitly call the `quotas_tenant_isolation` RLS policy a \"backstop\" for the app-level `api_key_id` filter, but every existing AC6 test only exercises the app's own repository (which always includes the filter), and even a raw filter-less query over the shared test fixture would be meaningless since the testcontainers connection is a Postgres superuser (superusers always bypass RLS regardless of `FORCE`). I provisioned a `NOBYPASSRLS` role mirroring production's `meterly_app`, connected as it, and issued a query with the `api_key_id` predicate **removed entirely** — proving the RLS policy alone still confines a tenant to its own rows, plus a fail-closed check when the tenant setting is unset. This is exactly the \"disable the primary control, prove the backstop fires\" shape the charter requires; it was previously uncovered.\n\n**Acceptance criteria:** 20/22 covered.\n- **AC20 (perf) left uncovered**: the real k6 load test runs and measures a true nearest-rank p95, but the test itself only asserts `sample_count > 0` (weak form). Measured p95 was **3362ms against a 50ms budget** — ~40x this same host's no-quota baseline (83.55ms), so not attributable solely to the known Docker/Windows overhead already flagged as a deferred finding on feature 1. I did not weaken/relax this or fabricate a pass; it's left uncovered with the full measurement recorded in `perf`.\n- **AC22 delegated to security** per `acceptance.md`'s `delegated_criteria`.\n\n**Resilience:** migration round-trip pass (0003 up→down→up, seeded rows, every constraint re-driven), 1 property-based (Hypothesis) test, concurrency pass (AC13, exact winner/loser counts asserted).\n\n**Test quality (advisory):** mutation testing could not run — `mutmut` refuses native Windows (no WSL available here) — recorded honestly as `quality_ok:false`, not fabricated. Adversarial review flagged 6 gaps (`.pipeline/test-quality.json`), most notably that AC20's own test doesn't gate on its stated budget (high severity) and that the concurrency test is timing-sensitive rather than deterministic (medium).\n\nFiles:\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\tests\\integration\\test_quotas_rls_backstop.py` (new)\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\test-results.json` (new)\n- `C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\test-quality.json` (new)"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":304,"cache_read_input_tokens":138945,"output_tokens":1248,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":304},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":1248,"cache_read_input_tokens":138945,"cac